<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-06T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-06T13:00:00-05:00" n="769" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d769">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">093.112/659a: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi>
                                (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Harriman</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-06T14:00:00-04:00">March 6,
                                    1944—2 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>491. Personal for the Ambassador. We do not yet have a definite and final
                            solution of the decorations problem insofar as the military is
                            concerned, although, as it now stands, battlefield decorations may be
                            permitted but officers engaged in supply operations, such as lend lease,
                                <pb facs="0846" n="836" xml:id="pg_836"/> would not be permitted to
                            accept. Additional information will follow as soon as possible on that
                            aspect of the problem.</p>
                        <p>As to civilian officials of the Government, there is a statute<note n="84" xml:id="d769fn1">Approved January 31, 1881; 21 Stat.
                                604.</note> Which definitely precludes acceptance unless authorized
                            by Act of Congress.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Stettinius</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>